Metadata about the exchange.
Details about how to contact a person or an organization.
Details about a call for service received from a person alerting an authority of a situation.
A person who places a call for service.
An employment of a person.
Details about a physical location.
A human being.
A motor-driven conveyance designed to carry its operator, and optionally passengers and cargo, over land.
Indicates the severity of a fire and the corresponding response based on procedure (e.g. three alarm fire).
Call type. e.g., Alarm, Burglary, Fire, Accident.
Text indicating the sub-type of the call (e.g. Robbery Alarm, Fire Alarm, Intrusion Alarm).
The priority assigned to the call based on the type of call (burglary, shooting, etc.) and other additional information provided by the caller.
Details about general comments being exchanged.
The date and time a comment was made.
e.g. Law Enforcement Officer, Victim, Witness, Suspect.
A business or person which employs a person.
An organization capable of bearing legal rights and responsibilities.
A location identified by two or more streets which intersect.
Text that specifically identifies a particular cell tower.
Text that specifically identifies a particular cell sector.
Date/Time that the coordinates were recorded by the device in UTC.
A confidence measure derived from the number of cell sites, distance of the coordinates recorded from the cell site, accuracy of measurement of the coordinates and is typically expressed in meters.
A combination of names and/or titles by which a person is known.
Information that further qualifies primary data; data about data.
Uniquely identifies a computer terminal device.
The date/time that the exchange was submitted.

Message Sequence Number uniquely identifies a message from a specific application or service provider. Used for auditing purposes, to track messages for troubleshooting, and to tie results to the originating request.
Metadata about the exchange.
